WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.160
&gt;&gt; Great, so welcome to this special edition
of the "Authors at Google" series. Today we

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:10.450
are specifically focusing on the National
School Lunch Program Reform and we have Ann

00:00:10.450 --> 00:00:17.410
Cooper in conversation with our very own Olivia
Wu here, and Ann Cooper is also known as the

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:20.620
"Renegade Lunch Lady". She is a chef, nutrition
services director, consultant, author, public

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:35.100
speaker, and advocate for practical nutrition
reform. And, did you know that our very own

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:43.280
chef, Olivia Wu, before becoming the Executive
Chef at Oasis was actually a journalist? She

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:50.930
is a staff reporter for the San Francisco
Chronicle. She is a food consultant and public

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:58.150
relations specialist. She specializes in Asian
cuisine and culture and fusion cuisine, seafood

00:00:58.150 --> 00:01:02.390
and sustainability and believe it or not,
they were actually both roommates. So you

00:01:02.390 --> 00:01:03.780
may remember that Alice Waters came here last
year to share her vision for the delicious

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:11.110
food revolution and Ann Cooper's actually
the person that Alice Waters and the Chez

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:16.180
Panisse Foundation helped hire to make that
vision a reality so she helped eliminate nearly

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:21.999
all the processed foods that were served within
the Berkley Unified School District. She introduced

00:01:21.999 --> 00:01:29.649
fresh and organic foods into the daily menu
and all while staying within the food district's

00:01:29.649 --> 00:01:36.270
budget and then she has since moved to Boulder
to keep spreading the change so please welcome

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:38.610
Chef Ann Cooper and Olivia Wu.

00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:39.610
[applause]

00:01:39.610 --> 00:01:44.009
Olivia Wu: Welcome. It's an honor to have
you here. You've been to Google many times

00:01:44.009 --> 00:01:51.630
and we've sat around and talked so much about
how your day went, what the kids ate and what

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:55.799
they didn't eat, and what your staff did so
I hope to just replicate some of that and

00:01:55.799 --> 00:02:01.340
there is a small enough group here that maybe
everybody can come up to the fireside with

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:03.729
your questions. We have lots of questions
for you in the next three hours but I'm just

00:02:03.729 --> 00:02:09.390
going to kind of turn you on and let you talk
[laughs] But you turned the food chain around

00:02:09.390 --> 00:02:17.720
here at Berkeley and now you are at Boulder
doing all of Boulder County. What are some

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:24.220
of the similarities? What are new challenges?
What are the 'ah ha' moments that make you

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:33.320
go "This is what I've been able to do and
I'll do it all again or this is new" so talk

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.060
to us about that.

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:41.020
Ann Cooper: Well, when I came to Berkeley,
I came because Alice Waters asked me to come

00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:47.121
and I had been doing this in New York and
she said come to Berkeley. I had also had

00:02:47.121 --> 00:02:52.570
been asked to go to Harlem and work in Harlem
so I said yes to both and I was working half

00:02:52.570 --> 00:02:56.920
time in Harlem and half time in Berkeley,
commuting back and forth and trying to redo

00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:01.840
some schools in New York City as well. And
I didn't actually think I'd ever take over

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:04.840
the district. I thought I was just going to
be a consultant but after being a consultant

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:09.610
for a year, I eventually took over the district
and because Alice and her foundation had been

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:14.420
working here for ten years and also the Center
for Equal Literacy, there was a real strong

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:19.360
movement in Berkeley to make change. However,
the food was spectacularly bad. I mean, the

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:25.410
kids had a five day rotating cycle of chicken
nuggets, extremo burritos, pizza pockets,

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:30.620
corn dogs, and grilled cheese sandwiches,
all preprocessed, all prepared, all in plastic

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:33.150
and that's what the kids ate and so you'd
think Alice, Berkeley, you know, there's a

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:38.122
real disconnect but that's the kind of food
we had. It took four years and it was a real

00:03:38.122 --> 00:03:43.200
hard process and even though we had a lot
of parent's support in some areas, we had

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:48.150
a lot of push back in others and we had a
tremendous amount of push back from the kids

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:55.160
but you know, it was a process and it took
four years but Berkeley was small. It was

00:03:55.160 --> 00:04:00.900
sixteen schools, 9,600 kids, and I could actually
go to every school in one day. I had this

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:06.130
huge support system, both financial and resources.
The foundation raised a million and a half

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:10.710
dollars over the time I was there to help
the school district make the change, then

00:04:10.710 --> 00:04:15.020
now the school's districts nutrition services
is totally budget neutral and financially

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:20.430
viable, sustainable, systemic and all now
but it took a long time. I also had a superintendent

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:24.530
in the school board who are very supportive
and superintendent who basically stood in

00:04:24.530 --> 00:04:28.280
front of me and said, you know, and protected
me and said, "We are going to make these changes,

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:36.199
it's going to be painful, it's going to work."
So when I get asked, I get recruited to go

00:04:36.199 --> 00:04:39.539
to Boulder in a sort of very similar community
and they said, "Yeah! We've got all this parent

00:04:39.539 --> 00:04:45.150
support and we've got a community that's going
to support us. We've done this great survey

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:51.289
and everyone really wants this." And the superintendent
in the school board was like, "Yeah, yeah.

00:04:51.289 --> 00:04:55.410
Everybody's ready and we're going to do this."
And so I took the job there. It's much bigger.

00:04:55.410 --> 00:05:02.259
It's 48 schools spread over 550 square miles.
I have a 175 employees and none of which,

00:05:02.259 --> 00:05:08.830
or very few of which, were really motivated
to make these kind of very difficult changes.

00:05:08.830 --> 00:05:14.870
Even though they have surveyed the parents,
most of the parents who answered the survey

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:22.100
I think were from Boulder proper but we, the
district, encompasses ten communities and

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:26.759
literally 65 miles from one end of our district
to the other. So even though the Boulder parents

00:05:26.759 --> 00:05:31.599
thought this was really great and they raised
half a million dollars and they were doing

00:05:31.599 --> 00:05:35.590
all this great stuff, there was all these
other parents and so I'm getting pushed, I've

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:39.150
been there since July and I'm getting pushed
back like that, "I feed my kids chicken nuggets

00:05:39.150 --> 00:05:42.940
at home. Who the hell are you to tell me not
to? Why do you get to decide our kids can't

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:47.091
have chicken nuggets or tater tots or high
fructose corn syrup or popsicles or Pop Tarts

00:05:47.091 --> 00:05:53.259
or you know, candy, we use it." And then other
challenges, the same Boulder parents who would

00:05:53.259 --> 00:05:57.300
write checks of ten and twenty thousand dollars
at the drop off a hat won't make their kids

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:01.020
eat the food, you know? Because their kids
would rather have sushi or you know the kids

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:09.870
say, "I don't really want that, I want this.
I want you to get me this." You know, so I'm

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:14.150
struggling with the same parents who want
me there are the same parents who raised a

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:17.999
half million dollars to get this program off
and running aren't actually having their kids

00:06:17.999 --> 00:06:22.309
eat so we run in there believing that we could
raise participation which is how you make

00:06:22.309 --> 00:06:27.629
these programs sustainable and we've only
been able to raise it five percent which is

00:06:27.629 --> 00:06:32.569
just not enough. So, in some ways, you've
either got the similar demographic but in

00:06:32.569 --> 00:06:38.349
other ways, it's very different and it's so
spread out it's really hard. I mean, I now

00:06:38.349 --> 00:06:42.559
have five managers and they can't even get
to every school every day so we try and get

00:06:42.559 --> 00:06:46.150
to every school every other day now but it's
a lot of transition work.

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:49.020
Olivia Wu: How many schools are we talking?

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:50.099
Ann Cooper: 48.

00:06:50.099 --> 00:06:51.539
Olivia Wu: 48 schools?

00:06:51.539 --> 00:06:52.620
Ann Cooper: Yeah.

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:58.729
Olivia Wu: Yeah, that's a lot. You're the
most wired digital lady that I know. You have

00:06:58.729 --> 00:07:05.499
so many toys so the obvious question for me
is you know Google. We want to be involved

00:07:05.499 --> 00:07:11.830
and we want to make a difference. What do
we do? Do we find five hundred other anchor

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:18.490
boosts? Do we go in on the policy level? Do
we help raise money? Do we help market? What

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:19.599
can we do?

00:07:19.599 --> 00:07:23.930
Ann Cooper: There is so many things and I
love that question because I need so much

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:28.800
help. You know, Berkeley or Boulder or any
of the local communities you might have kids

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:34.680
in or know where kids are, we cannot fix this
one school at a time. There is a 125,000 schools

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:38.960
in this country. We cannot fix it one school
at a time. There is almost fifteen thousand

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:44.050
school districts. We can't even fix it one
district at a time. It's impossible, we have

00:07:44.050 --> 00:07:50.200
to change it at the USDA level. For the very
first time in my whole career on school food,

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:54.479
I'm very optimistic and then we have a President
who actually talked about kids and food and

00:07:54.479 --> 00:07:59.169
health in the same sentence. The last President
who talked about kids and food was Reagan

00:07:59.169 --> 00:08:06.050
who made ketchup a vegetable so I'm very optimistic
with Obama. We now have a First Lady who not

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:10.229
only planted a garden at the White House that
I have been fortunate enough to go to but

00:08:10.229 --> 00:08:15.409
has a great personal chef whose invested in
this and now they have food policies, and

00:08:15.409 --> 00:08:20.180
she has just announced to Council of Mayors
that she is taking on, and even in President

00:08:20.180 --> 00:08:24.939
Obama's State of the Union, they are taking
on childhood obesity and she specifically

00:08:24.939 --> 00:08:30.229
said in her speech to the mayors that what
had to happen in schools. I've met with the

00:08:30.229 --> 00:08:34.870
Deputy Secretary of Agriculture, Kathleen
Merrigan, who used to be on the National Organic

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:38.829
Standards Board and I was on the National
Organic Standards Board but I went on right

00:08:38.829 --> 00:08:44.050
after her, and she is very interested in this
stuff and I met with the Undersecretary that's

00:08:44.050 --> 00:08:49.470
over School Lunch, Janey
Thornton, and she's interested in making change.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:54.180
I think the most optimistic thing or the thing
that makes me most optimistic is Arne Duncan.

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:59.449
I haven't met with him but I've met with his
staff and his staff said to me, "We can not

00:08:59.449 --> 00:09:04.620
close the achievement gap in America unless
we fix school lunch." So for the first time,

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:08.720
the Secretary of Ag and the Secretary of Education
are actually talking about these two things

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:13.300
because the Secretary of Education is over
education and the Secretary of Ag is over

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:17.829
school lunch so there's two very divergent
things. From Google's point of view, there

00:09:17.829 --> 00:09:22.199
is so much you can do to help. I mean, one
of the things, any of you who are at lunch

00:09:22.199 --> 00:09:27.360
or we could show later, one of the things
that's happening right now is we are building

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:33.610
a web portal and these little bands that say
"I Matter, Feed Me Well" also have the URL

00:09:33.610 --> 00:09:38.100
for the web portal that we're building and
we're trying to build a web portal that will

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:43.050
have all the tools that every school district
in the country can use to make these changes.

00:09:43.050 --> 00:09:49.279
It has menus and recipes and technical tools
and videos and educational materials and a

00:09:49.279 --> 00:09:56.410
big community piece sort of AKA Facebook where
people can gather, so we are trying to build

00:09:56.410 --> 00:10:01.720
this. We partnered this past summer with Whole
Foods and we raised a million dollars to start

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:06.980
the process of building a portal, but one
of the things I've come to understand which

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:13.170
is very interesting is I thought much of this
up in my head and we've been struggling to

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:18.649
have the technology catch up to what we kind
of thought of, and so we're struggling with

00:10:18.649 --> 00:10:23.181
the technology to be able to build something
that's actually can do all the things that

00:10:23.181 --> 00:10:28.100
I think it needs to do and can be seen by
people in schools who can't get onto Facebook,

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:33.160
who can't get onto Twitter, and who can't
use YouTube or anything like that, so all

00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:38.990
schools ban all of that material, so how do
you have someplace where people can go that's

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:44.720
sort of outside of the social networking arena
that we all play in because schools can't

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:52.380
play in it. The other thing around that I
think, from a Google standpoint, we need,

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:59.940
you know, whether it's the Google phone or
the iPhone, we need some apps that can build

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:07.230
in that smartphone universe that school people
could like pull up recipes, that they could

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:10.750
get answers to questions right from their
phone because many of them are out in the

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:15.279
field and they may not be able to get to their
computers so that's another thing we're looking

00:11:15.279 --> 00:11:20.470
at, like how do we develop that and what is
it that we really want to develop around that.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:29.009
The other thing is on February 8th, that the
Secretary of Agriculture, Tom Vilsack, is

00:11:29.009 --> 00:11:33.690
going to make a speech and the speech is going
to be taking about school lunch. Right after

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:38.370
the speech, my foundation is starting a national
write-in campaign to get a million moms and

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:46.079
dads or parents or caregivers to write to
Tom Vilsack and Kathleen Merrigan at the USDA

00:11:46.079 --> 00:11:51.589
and the Senate and Representatives from Congress.
We are actually putting up the website with

00:11:51.589 --> 00:11:55.569
a map and you'll be able to click on the map
and we've got a letter that you'll be able

00:11:55.569 --> 00:11:59.649
to send in or customize the letter and send
it in. Getting information like that out would

00:11:59.649 --> 00:12:03.829
be really, really helpful so we are trying
to have the stuff go viral. We've made an

00:12:03.829 --> 00:12:08.980
animated video that we hope will help us.
A 90 second video can be like a PSA, it can

00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:13.360
be watched on smartphones or on computers
and we are trying to get a bunch of stuff

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:17.329
going viral so this is the year of the child
nutrition reauthorization that only happens

00:12:17.329 --> 00:12:23.430
every four or five years. This is where the
federal government decides how much money

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:27.879
they are going to give school and what the
guidelines are. The money thing is really

00:12:27.879 --> 00:12:33.930
important. Schools are now given $2,000.68
to feed a child for a day if it's a free child.

00:12:33.930 --> 00:12:37.509
Of that, traditionally two thirds goes to
payroll and overhead. That leaves us less

00:12:37.509 --> 00:12:41.561
then a dollar a day to feed a kid and if any
of you have been to Starbucks of late and

00:12:41.561 --> 00:12:48.139
gotten a venti latte or any of the other exotic,
you know, coffee shops, you'll know that you

00:12:48.139 --> 00:12:52.800
are paying four or five dollars so you know
we now have a world where we spend four or

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:58.279
five dollars more on our daily coffee then
we are spending on our kid's lunch so the

00:12:58.279 --> 00:13:03.030
dollar doesn't really get you enough but the
USDA does decide that. Also the USDA guidelines

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:07.779
around chicken nuggets, tater tots, chocolate
milk, high fructose corn syrup, transfat,

00:13:07.779 --> 00:13:12.941
popsicles, Pop Tarts, and corn dogs, that
is all allowed on the National School Lunch

00:13:12.941 --> 00:13:23.720
Program so it's not enough just to get money.
We absolutely have to get the guidelines changed.

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:30.949
Olivia Wu: Guidelines changed. Besides the
grassroots letter writing and getting to Vilsack,

00:13:30.949 --> 00:13:34.589
how can Google further--, with this?

00:13:34.589 --> 00:13:41.470
Ann Cooper: Well, I think it'll be an interesting
thing. I mean Google is sort of the center

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:46.920
of the, I mean from a Google outsider, someone
who Googles on like a million times a day

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:52.129
regular basis, you know, if Google is the
holder of information in the world, if any

00:13:52.129 --> 00:13:58.800
bit of information you want or think you want
can be gotten through Googling then that's

00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:03.449
a way to collect information so I guess the
question would be does Google want to push

00:14:03.449 --> 00:14:09.740
information and if Google did want to push
information, then it'd be really cool to be

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:16.810
able to, when people are Googling school lunch
or people that are interested in some of these

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:24.399
things to be able to have a message or have
specific sites that will support it. You know,

00:14:24.399 --> 00:14:29.310
when you go on Google and you'll see those
top ones and that's the ones that are sponsored

00:14:29.310 --> 00:14:34.910
sites so maybe there is a way to sponser sites
that are done by non-profits or sponsor sites

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:37.500
that are really pushing forward this mission.
Something like that.

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:38.730
Olivia Wu: Yes, Sir?

00:14:38.730 --> 00:14:43.959
&gt;&gt; We don't, put up the natural search results,
we won't alter those because that has to be,

00:14:43.959 --> 00:14:44.959
you know, fair and the better content of your
site has, whatever site it is, then the higher

00:14:44.959 --> 00:15:09.690
it'll interact in the rankings, but in terms
of like the ads, we do offer Google Grants

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:19.320
Program to do that so I don't know if you
guys have been taking part in that yet.

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:20.320
Ann Cooper: Uh uh. We haven't.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:21.420
&gt;&gt; Great, so those advertisements are free
and that Grants program is significant so

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:22.420
you should talk about that.

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:23.420
Ann Cooper: Cool. Great.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:24.420
Olivia Wu: Excellent. Yeah. So once, tell
me the sequence, the ideal sequence you see

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:29.700
things happening in, from policy down. How
do you think it should happen? And then maybe

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:34.889
from out here, we'll have ideas on how Google
fits in.

00:15:34.889 --> 00:15:41.399
Ann Cooper: In a perfect world, and we know
we're in such an imperfect world, the problem

00:15:41.399 --> 00:15:45.910
with the USDA guidelines and the money is
the USDA was founded to be the marketing arm

00:15:45.910 --> 00:15:52.749
for agribusiness and their mission in the
world, and it may be changing now, but their

00:15:52.749 --> 00:15:57.780
mission historically has been to promote big
agriculture and for the most part that big

00:15:57.780 --> 00:16:01.889
agriculture exports to other countries so
literally they are the marketing arm for Monsanto

00:16:01.889 --> 00:16:05.190
and DuPont and ADM and all these big huge
companies.

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:06.779
Olivia Wu: Chemical companies.

00:16:06.779 --> 00:16:12.160
Ann Cooper: Chemical companies that have now
decided that food companies and as well, you

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:16.420
know, Monsanto and DuPont produce Agent Orange
and stain resistant carpet. They control 90%

00:16:16.420 --> 00:16:22.509
of the commercially produced seeds in America,
so this is a crazy paradigm, but as well they

00:16:22.509 --> 00:16:27.870
also support a lot of companies through the
commodity food program and our tax dollars

00:16:27.870 --> 00:16:35.420
spend about 45 billion dollars a year subsidizing
corn, soy, rice, wheat, and I think one other,

00:16:35.420 --> 00:16:42.050
cotton, so the government buys all of the
stuff and the reason why sugar is so cheap

00:16:42.050 --> 00:16:46.740
is because corn is so highly subsidized and
the reason we have high fructose corn syrup

00:16:46.740 --> 00:16:52.100
in everything from hamburgers, to hamburgers
to hot dogs to gum to soda is because the

00:16:52.100 --> 00:16:57.290
corn is so overproduced and so cheap that
now they make it into high fructose corn syrup

00:16:57.290 --> 00:17:05.250
and so the USDA gets to decide what's allowed
in the food. They buy this food, although

00:17:05.250 --> 00:17:08.880
it's not actually food because none of that
corn goes into high fructose syrup would ever

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:14.540
be eaten, so they buy the stuff and then subsidize
to make this processed stuff that we send

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:20.589
into schools and to give you a perfect example
of how awful the system is, a year ago January,

00:17:20.589 --> 00:17:28.120
a year ago this month, for some reason Tyson
decided they needed a bail out, so the USDA

00:17:28.120 --> 00:17:33.150
bailed out Tyson for a 143 million dollars
so they bought a 143 million dollars worth

00:17:33.150 --> 00:17:37.840
of chicken from Tyson while there may not
even have been chicken but there is the virtual

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:41.840
chicken. There is the idea that they needed
money so the government gave them the money

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:46.539
in exchange for chicken. So then Tyson comes
to schools all over the country, school districts

00:17:46.539 --> 00:17:50.450
and says, "The government just gave us all
