medicine. You know, health and human services
recently came out and said if we don't change

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:08.240
how we're eating, every single person in our
country is going to be overweight or obese

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:15.060
by 2040, you know? In 30 years. It's crazy,
it's crazy.

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:20.060
Olivia Wu: What other matrix should we be
looking at?

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:25.520
Ann Cooper: Well, the thing, the unfortunate
thing that everybody wants to know is if we

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:30.800
feed kids better food, will it raise their
academic performance. This is a very, very,

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:31.800
very hard -

00:35:31.800 --> 00:35:33.589
Olivia Wu: Well, duh.

00:35:33.589 --> 00:35:39.400
Ann Cooper: Well, instead of like "Duh". Okay,
so when any of us like eat crap all day or

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:42.460
don't eat, how do we feel? We feel really
awful and when is it that we want sugar or

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:46.470
caffeine? 3 in the afternoon when we skip
lunch. I mean, we as adults know what happens

00:35:46.470 --> 00:35:49.789
to our body, you know. We don't?

00:35:49.789 --> 00:35:56.829
&gt;&gt; We don't pay attention to our bodies as
adults. What are you talking about? [laughs]

00:35:56.829 --> 00:36:03.630
Ann Cooper: Okay. Maybe as adults we actually
have the knowledge to pay attention to our

00:36:03.630 --> 00:36:10.510
bodies if we wanted to and with all that being
said, we do know that kids that eat a diet

00:36:10.510 --> 00:36:14.710
high in sugar, refined sugar and refined flour,
are really often diagnosed with ADD, ADHD,

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:18.630
and dyslexia. We know that these same kids
are almost always in the office, that they

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:24.150
have real poor performance and real poor behavior
but everybody wants the study that's going

00:36:24.150 --> 00:36:29.050
to link better food to academic performance
because of No Child Left Behind. Well, No

00:36:29.050 --> 00:36:34.511
Child Left Behind pretty much leaves every
child behind. It is a crazy system, it's really

00:36:34.511 --> 00:36:41.890
bad from the food service point of view. There
was just a study done in England by Jamie

00:36:41.890 --> 00:36:47.960
Oliver's group, a group run by Jamie Oliver
just did a study and did actually show over

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:53.440
there that the food reduction in refined sugars
and refined flours in more whole foods does

00:36:53.440 --> 00:36:58.490
indeed increase academic performance. What
I actually think it does is not increase academic

00:36:58.490 --> 00:37:02.010
performance, it increases our ability to focus
and think. You know, when you give kids a

00:37:02.010 --> 00:37:05.720
lot of sugar they just get really high and
they crash and I was working with some kids

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:08.291
in Harlem one time and we were making a PBS
show and they're just hanging around and the

00:37:08.291 --> 00:37:12.620
kids are a little nervous and there're cameras
everywhere and I said, "What did you guys

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:15.550
have for breakfast?" And I came from a little
town in the middle of nowhere and they said,

00:37:15.550 --> 00:37:19.190
"Snack Crack". I'm in Harlem now and I said,
"Oh. They said snack crack. It's an English

00:37:19.190 --> 00:37:28.710
topping." And they said, "You know, our parents
go out in the street and get crack to get

00:37:28.710 --> 00:37:36.160
high all we need is 20 ounce soda and candy
on the way to school and we get just as high,

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:39.380
you know." I mean, this is what the kids,
13 year olds were saying, so they know what

00:37:39.380 --> 00:37:44.400
we are doing to them and I say 'we' because
you know, the adults have to make choices.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:49.280
I mean, schools are drug free zones, schools
are alcohol free zones, they should be junk

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:50.280
food free zones.

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:57.170
&gt;&gt; Actually just quickly, would you talk about
open campuses versus closed campuses? I don't

00:37:57.170 --> 00:37:59.710
know the status of Berkeley and I don't know
the status of Boulder and is that going to

00:37:59.710 --> 00:38:01.369
be required for a big change like this.

00:38:01.369 --> 00:38:08.020
Ann Cooper: Yeah. Both Berkeley and Boulder
have open campuses. It's a really crazy system.

00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:11.510
I do not know why we would want to send our
children -

00:38:11.510 --> 00:38:12.760
&gt;&gt; Tell people what that means.

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:20.030
Ann Cooper: Okay. So what open campus means
is that in many high schools across the country,

00:38:20.030 --> 00:38:24.350
the students are allowed to leave campus for
up to an hour in the middle of the day to

00:38:24.350 --> 00:38:30.680
go somewhere and do something. The idea is
that you are letting them go off campus for

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:35.440
lunch. These are, you know, sometimes as young
as 14, 15 year old, 16 year old kids who you

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:41.260
send to school because you think that they're
being educated and you know given some supervision

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:46.450
that you then allow them to go where they
want. One of the things that happens when

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:51.060
you let them go where they want is they don't
eat the food on campus and they go eat junk

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:53.660
food wherever they can because they don't
want to spend a lot of money and they can

00:38:53.660 --> 00:38:58.050
get a lot of calories and a lot of sugar and
a lot of fat for 99 cents at some fast food

00:38:58.050 --> 00:39:04.589
place. Schools are starting to turn that around,
it makes no sense to me. Why would you, why

00:39:04.589 --> 00:39:10.000
would we want to send our kids to school and
then assume that they're going to spend some

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:15.300
amount of time without any supervision doing
whatever they're going to be doing and eating

00:39:15.300 --> 00:39:18.820
and drinking and smoking whatever they are
going to be doing and yeah, I mean that happens

00:39:18.820 --> 00:39:26.320
to us all at some point when we are probably
a little older then teenagers, but I do think

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:30.010
we should close campuses. The big challenge
on closing campuses now is they didn't make

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:34.380
schools big enough, you know? Because they
started letting kids out so now, like in Berkeley,

00:39:34.380 --> 00:39:40.310
there's one high school, 32 hundred students,
they built a beautiful new cafeteria and it

00:39:40.310 --> 00:39:45.680
seats 400. Duh! There's no way I can feed
them and Boulder's done the same thing so

00:39:45.680 --> 00:39:50.130
schools have saved money by building buildings
that don't have cafeteria seating for the

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:55.230
kids because they figure the kids are going
to go away so it's, "Oh good, we don't have

00:39:55.230 --> 00:40:00.380
to watch them for an hour." Well, you know
that's not -- if we are educating the whole

00:40:00.380 --> 00:40:04.450
child for the whole day that we have them
with us, we have to understand that the lunch

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:08.340
period is part of the educational experience.
It's part of the whole child.

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:20.910
Olivia Wu: Do we know the policy people and
the Congress people who are most friendly

00:40:20.910 --> 00:40:25.420
to childhood nutrition and such issues?

00:40:25.420 --> 00:40:31.500
Ann Cooper: Yes. There will be up on the new
website, there's some other websites that

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:36.599
do have them all listed. We don't have them
listed on our website but we will have all

00:40:36.599 --> 00:40:40.400
the information up there.

00:40:40.400 --> 00:40:46.730
&gt;&gt; I have a question that relates to that.
It seemed to me for a long time that the real

00:40:46.730 --> 00:40:51.280
way to victory on this is to make this a bipartisan
issue which of course it inherently is. It's

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:58.730
about children and it's very hard to meet
any elected official who doesn't understand

00:40:58.730 --> 00:41:05.609
that that's fundamentally really the constituency.
Of course, it very quickly can become a political

00:41:05.609 --> 00:41:09.320
and bipartisan issue when I think grownups
get involved.

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:10.380
Ann Cooper: [laughs]

00:41:10.380 --> 00:41:16.859
&gt;&gt; And so I actually really would love to
see, you know, a way to get children speaking

00:41:16.859 --> 00:41:22.670
more actively and I challenge the people of
Google to help make this happen. To let children

00:41:22.670 --> 00:41:26.579
more speak to their experience directly to
share their experiences with people and to

00:41:26.579 --> 00:41:30.329
be the advocates for this change,
because what we're seeing more and more is

00:41:30.329 --> 00:41:35.220
that these polarizing issues including healthcare
has become very, very difficult for people

00:41:35.220 --> 00:41:41.640
to understand, for the electorates to understand,
for Democrats who originally thought it was

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:46.710
a great idea to understand, for Republicans
who felt that they were going to have to support

00:41:46.710 --> 00:41:52.809
it to support it. Most people now feel, as
you said a moment ago, it's kind of dead in

00:41:52.809 --> 00:41:56.430
the water. You know, the children are incredibly
powerful here. They can cut through a lot

00:41:56.430 --> 00:42:02.270
of this but we have to find a way to give
them a voice.

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:06.830
Ann Cooper: There's a couple of interesting
things happening. There is a couple of different

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:12.950
groups. One is the Healthy Schools Campaign
that are actually having kids do a set of

00:42:12.950 --> 00:42:18.100
"Iron Chef" competitions and the winners of
the one in Chicago actually got to meet Sam

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:22.270
Kass, who is the chef at the White House,
or Michelle's chef and working on these issues.

00:42:22.270 --> 00:42:27.050
They actually just two days ago served the
winning recipe from this year at all the Chicago

00:42:27.050 --> 00:42:32.069
schools so there is this group that's doing
that. The other thing that's happening is

00:42:32.069 --> 00:42:33.749
a video competition which is, what's the name
of it?

00:42:33.749 --> 00:42:35.080
&gt;&gt; The National Farm to School Network.

00:42:35.080 --> 00:42:45.930
Ann Cooper: The National Farm to School Network
is hosting a video competition and we are

00:42:45.930 --> 00:42:49.711
part of the sponsors of this and they are
getting kids all across the country to make

00:42:49.711 --> 00:42:55.790
little videos and upload them about what their
school food is and what it should be so there's

00:42:55.790 --> 00:43:00.391
two projects that are going on right now,
and we are working with both of them.

00:43:00.391 --> 00:43:03.480
&gt;&gt; And that's on Youtube by the way.

00:43:03.480 --> 00:43:07.650
Ann Cooper: That's on Youtube? Yeah, okay.
That again is FarmtoSchool.org.

00:43:07.650 --> 00:43:15.910
Olivia Wu: Okay. A lot of data has already
been gathered. What we don't want to do at

00:43:15.910 --> 00:43:25.079
Google is repeat any of that and a lot of
studies have been done, short of the one you're

00:43:25.079 --> 00:43:32.960
talking that connects academic performance
for that, but is there any area in data collection

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:35.000
that has not been done out there?

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:44.480
Ann Cooper: Well, there has not been a really
unbiased national study done about what's

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:51.079
really happening in schools. On our website,
we are going to have areas where there's feasibility

00:43:51.079 --> 00:43:56.242
studies that have been done so you can see
them and a lot of this information will be

00:43:56.242 --> 00:44:02.420
on the Lunch Box site but what I don't think
has happened is a real comprehensive look

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:07.400
at what we are feeding our kids all across
the country. The School Nutrition Association

00:44:07.400 --> 00:44:11.790
has done it, but not all school districts
are involved and they really have it bent

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:16.580
to make it look good, so I don't know that
we've ever collected really what kids are

00:44:16.580 --> 00:44:21.410
eating. Like New York City, I think on the
New York Times today, New York City just changed

00:44:21.410 --> 00:44:27.500
the fat content of the milk and saved, I don't
know, how many billions of calories, but we

00:44:27.500 --> 00:44:31.660
shouldn't serve chocolate milk in schools
and we haven't been able to get chocolate

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:36.619
milk out of schools. So really understand
what we are feeding our kids and the health

00:44:36.619 --> 00:44:42.249
ramifications. I just don't think we've done
a good enough job figuring that piece out.

00:44:42.249 --> 00:44:48.540
&gt;&gt; You mentioned a list of people in Congress
who are friendly toward healthy food in the

00:44:48.540 --> 00:44:54.619
schools. Have you identified people who are
less then friendly who are more on the agribusiness

00:44:54.619 --> 00:45:00.940
side and more to understand their argument
and their problems to be solved as well so

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:03.450
that hopefully it could be a bipartisan issue?

00:45:03.450 --> 00:45:10.480
Ann Cooper: Well, I don't have that list but
it'd be pretty easy to make.

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:11.809
&gt;&gt; About half, right?

00:45:11.809 --> 00:45:13.589
Ann Cooper: Yes. Nicole?

00:45:13.589 --> 00:45:19.521
Nicole &gt;&gt; Children Tips and La Vida Locavore
has a list of the unfriendlies on her website.

00:45:19.521 --> 00:45:26.900
Ann Cooper: Okay, so there's a website. LaVidaLocavore.org
and she has both the- for and against people.

00:45:26.900 --> 00:45:34.090
The people are not against healthy food for
kids but they are by in large from these states

00:45:34.090 --> 00:45:39.500
where all of their money comes from corn or
soy, and there is basically not much good

00:45:39.500 --> 00:45:44.240
you can do with GMA corn or soy except make
it into this stuff that goes into school food

00:45:44.240 --> 00:45:45.791
or healthcare or things like that.

00:45:45.791 --> 00:45:55.359
&gt;&gt; Related question. Have we learned much
from the fight against tobacco and how to

00:45:55.359 --> 00:46:01.240
work with those states that are dependant
upon tobacco because there's been, as a child

00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:04.410
of the 70's, tremendous progress in the last
thirty years.

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:08.830
Ann Cooper: You know, Michael Pollan talks
about this issue a lot and you know, there's

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:17.119
a lot of people who talk about this big ad
and how it points into the cigarette smoking

00:46:17.119 --> 00:46:23.690
issue. The thing that comes up, and you hear
is the pushback all the time, is there is

00:46:23.690 --> 00:46:29.700
nothing positive about smoking and you didn't
need to smoke. Everyone needs to eat and there's

00:46:29.700 --> 00:46:37.800
this social component of that. There's a historical
component of that. There is the familiar component

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:43.710
of that and big business just keeps pushing
it as choices, choices, exercise, yet they

00:46:43.710 --> 00:46:48.829
spend twenty billion dollars a year marketing
non nutrient foods to kids so I think a lot

00:46:48.829 --> 00:46:53.880
of people have thought how to connect these
and I do think, we've seen some people like

00:46:53.880 --> 00:47:00.210
trying to sue McDonalds and then now we have
these anti veggie laws where you can't sue.

00:47:00.210 --> 00:47:05.230
I don't know if you guys remember when Oprah
said that she wouldn't eat a hamburger again

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:09.170
from the National Cattlemen's Association
sued her for billions of dollars. She won

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:14.730
but it cost her a billion to win, you know
so there's these anti defamation for vegetable

00:47:14.730 --> 00:47:23.069
laws so you can't say a food isn't good, you
know. It's crazy so people have sort of put

00:47:23.069 --> 00:47:30.090
their toe in. I think the way to go after
this and it's really hard to say you have

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:36.970
to sue the government, but I'd love to see
us think about a way to do a class action

00:47:36.970 --> 00:47:40.349
suit against some of these big companies and
against the government that's feeding our

00:47:40.349 --> 00:47:51.290
kids that allows this food into schools, but
it's really hard to sue a government [laughs]

00:47:51.290 --> 00:47:53.270
I want to do it! We can do it.[laughs]

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:57.690
&gt;&gt; Well, you and I have been talking for a
long time about suing the government and I'm

00:47:57.690 --> 00:47:58.690
in. I'm ready [laughs]

00:47:58.690 --> 00:48:06.510
I'm just going to say maybe you want to mention
Kelly Brownell who recently had that pretty

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:12.420
interesting report that he issued. This is
a guy at Yale who is very interested in the

00:48:12.420 --> 00:48:19.452
parallels between anti smoking sentiment and
the movement that grew up to really kind of

00:48:19.452 --> 00:48:20.452
take that over.

00:48:20.452 --> 00:48:22.239
Ann Cooper: But which report exactly?

00:48:22.239 --> 00:48:30.020
&gt;&gt; It's about nine months old and actually
I can just send it but it's pretty interesting

00:48:30.020 --> 00:48:34.180
because it actually doesn't deal so much with
the litigious aspects as the cultural aspects

00:48:34.180 --> 00:48:40.120
of marketing and it's really about the mistakes
that people in the food movement have made

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:44.870
and the mistakes that people in the tobacco
movement are making and how we can kind of

00:48:44.870 --> 00:48:50.910
try to capitalize on it but I appreciated
his study because it was more nuanced and

00:48:50.910 --> 00:48:55.720
it did deal of course with this huge problem,
which is that we all have to eat, but it really

00:48:55.720 --> 00:48:58.920
tried to talk a lot about the kind of marketing
shifts.

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:03.210
Ann Cooper: Well, one of things at one of
the studies that has just really recently

00:49:03.210 --> 00:49:08.540
come out too is really finally proving this
thing about marketing to kids and that these

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:15.619
big companies are so focused on marketing
this non nutrient foods to kids and you know,

00:49:15.619 --> 00:49:20.390
kids are basically brainwashed over this stuff,
but Kelly Brownell from the Rudd Center at

00:49:20.390 --> 00:49:26.020
Yale has been studying obesity in kids and
adults for a long time and looking at all

00:49:26.020 --> 00:49:27.020
of these issues.

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:39.750
Olivia Wu: I want to bring the conversation
back around to just what you do on the ground

00:49:39.750 --> 00:49:47.040
every day and what the kids are like. So describe
for me what a kid's lunch was starting with

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:52.750
chicken nuggets and then describe to us for
the dollar and the commodities that you got,

00:49:52.750 --> 00:49:57.569
what kind of meals they got by the end of
your four year tenure at Berkeley.

00:49:57.569 --> 00:50:03.710
Ann Cooper: In Berkeley, we started with the
food I told you. The real crappy commodity

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:04.710
food.

00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:08.100
Olivia Wu: So it was chicken nuggets, chocolate
milk.

00:50:08.100 --> 00:50:12.619
Ann Cooper: It was chicken nuggets, corn dogs,
extremo burritos, grilled cheese sandwiches,

00:50:12.619 --> 00:50:18.950
and pizza pockets and they are all pre frozen
and pre made things and they had chocolate

00:50:18.950 --> 00:50:24.930
milk and they had all kinds of sugary 'desserty'
things and stuff like that.

00:50:24.930 --> 00:50:27.210
Olivia Wu: So how many calories was a meal
like?

00:50:27.210 --> 00:50:31.049
Ann Cooper&gt;&gt; A typical meal like that tends
to be about a thousand calories and it tends

00:50:31.049 --> 00:50:39.270
to be 2,000 milligrams of sodium which is
really more than a daily dose so that's what

00:50:39.270 --> 00:50:40.270
it tends to be.

00:50:40.270 --> 00:50:41.420
Olivia Wu: And calories from fat?

00:50:41.420 --> 00:50:48.700
Ann Cooper: Almost all. Like 60 percent calories
for that and usually a meal like that has

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:51.869
15 or 20 percent 'sat' fat even though the
law says ten.

00:50:51.869 --> 00:50:54.340
Olivia Wu: And then what was the change?

00:50:54.340 --> 00:50:55.869
&gt;&gt; That's within guidelines, right?

00:50:55.869 --> 00:51:02.240
Ann Cooper: Well, it's going outside the guidelines.
There's no guidelines on sugar or sodium.

00:51:02.240 --> 00:51:08.140
You are supposed to stay under 35 percent
fat and under 10 percent 'sat' fat but because

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:15.170
the way a lot of it works, some people don't
but you can balance it over the course of

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:19.710
a week, so then you feed them something else
that doesn't have so much fat one day and

00:51:19.710 --> 00:51:23.819
you can balance out, so there's no law on
how much you can feed kids. There is also

00:51:23.819 --> 00:51:30.589
no maximum calorie count which is really,
really old and silly. They tell you that you

00:51:30.589 --> 00:51:38.270
can feed kids two to three thousand calories.
It's like, "Huh? Do you not know there's an

00:51:38.270 --> 00:51:42.750
obesity crisis?" But again, their job is to
promote agriculture and the easiest way to

00:51:42.750 --> 00:51:45.970
promote agriculture is corn and soy, because
that's what we grow in this country. So now

00:51:45.970 --> 00:51:51.450
in Berkeley, although I haven't been there
this year but when I left last year, instead

00:51:51.450 --> 00:51:55.730
of chicken nuggets there'd be roast chicken
and instead of tater tots, there'd be roast

00:51:55.730 --> 00:51:59.880
potatoes. There'd be a fresh vegetable and
there were full salad bars in every school

00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:06.880
every day, local organic milk. No desserts
and no high fructose corn syrup, no transfats,

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:13.550
all whole grains and that's the same way we
are walking towards in Boulder. We are certainly

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:18.890
not in Boulder where Berkeley ended up because
we are just beginning in it but there's a

00:52:18.890 --> 00:52:22.069
lot of pushback from kids.
I mean, I just got an email today saying,

00:52:22.069 --> 00:52:28.200
"Why is it that we have to feed kids chicken
with bones?" and my comeback is, "Do you know

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:33.240
any chickens that are growing without bones?"
[laughs] and it's this crazy thing. Now that

00:52:33.240 --> 00:52:36.990
we've convinced kids that chicken nuggets
are actually chicken, who decided that chicken

00:52:36.990 --> 00:52:43.510
should be stars or giraffes or dinosaurs or
you know, fish? Chicken is chicken so why

00:52:43.510 --> 00:52:48.890
shouldn't chicken come on the bone? But you
know, the idea that kids don't even know the

00:52:48.890 --> 00:52:55.290
chicken has bones anymore and we are not supposed
to feed it to them. So in Boulder, our slowest

00:52:55.290 --> 00:53:00.500
day of the week now and we are working on
this in all kinds of ways, is chicken day

00:53:00.500 --> 00:53:06.960
because kids don't know how to actually eat
chicken anymore and because they think chicken

00:53:06.960 --> 00:53:13.430
nuggets is chicken, so it's a struggle to
make these changes and you know you would

00:53:13.430 --> 00:53:19.210
think roast potatoes for tater tots but there's
lot of kids who haven't eaten a fresh roasted

00:53:19.210 --> 00:53:25.970
potato, but they think that tater tots are
actually potatoes or that you know that instant

00:53:25.970 --> 00:53:31.460
potato stuff is what mashed potatoes are supposed
to taste like so when we serve kids real mashed

00:53:31.460 --> 00:53:35.781
potatoes, they go "Uggh!" and we make real
mac and cheese and the kids hate it, you know?

00:53:35.781 --> 00:53:39.780
One of our biggest complaints so far this
year is the mac and cheese and it's like,

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:45.990
"Okay, so we're cooking pasta and we've got
real cheddar cheese and we are making the

00:53:45.990 --> 00:53:50.660
cheese." But you know, they are used to Kraft
and that yellow amato powder that you mix

00:53:50.660 --> 00:54:01.700
with water and put some little pasta stuff
in it, so it's a huge change for kids and

00:54:01.700 --> 00:54:06.819
the other comment I got from kids is it's
not salty enough and this comes from the amount

00:54:06.819 --> 00:54:11.280
of salt they get in processed food versus
the amount of salt you'd actually salt something

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:17.589
with. So it's not salty enough, it's not spicy
enough because they are so used to this highly

00:54:17.589 --> 00:54:22.740
processed, really high sodium food. On the
other hand, what we are seeing now is kids

00:54:22.740 --> 00:54:27.920
10 years old who have kidney stones, because
of all the sodium in food. I mean, this is

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:33.230
crazy. Ten year old kids now with kidney stones
and you know pre teen kids with high blood

00:54:33.230 --> 00:54:38.440
pressure and heart disease and you know, it's
really awful.

00:54:38.440 --> 00:54:47.109
Olivia Wu: But on the other hand, the days
you would tell me about where a big bowl of

00:54:47.109 --> 00:54:51.760
Pink Lady organic apples disappeared. The
kids liked them?

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:57.240
Ann Cooper: Well, absolutely. I mean, in Berkeley
you had that model, you had cooking and gardening

00:54:57.240 --> 00:55:02.150
classes in every single school. That hands
on experiencial learning is invaluable. You

00:55:02.150 --> 00:55:06.740
got to have a way to touch the kids but by
the end of the Berkeley project, or by the

00:55:06.740 --> 00:55:11.049
time I left, because it's ongoing and sustainable,
I mean kids were really eating the food and

00:55:11.049 --> 00:55:15.920
the participation went up over three times.
When I started, we were doing about 500 thousand

00:55:15.920 --> 00:55:20.430
meals a year and I think they are going hit
almost two million this year so we really

00:55:20.430 --> 00:55:25.460
grew participation. The kids are eating. They
eat food, they eat vegetables, they eat off

00:55:25.460 --> 00:55:29.390
the salad bar. You know, not every kids eats
great every day but when you work with the

00:55:29.390 --> 00:55:33.482
kids, it's a process. I often say it takes
ten years. You got to get the kids when they

00:55:33.482 --> 00:55:37.119
are young and get them through high school
because if you just start in the middle, it's

00:55:37.119 --> 00:55:38.119
really hard.

00:55:38.119 --> 00:55:42.660
&gt;&gt; Okay, actually that's a great opportunity
for me to stand up. Why start in school? What

00:55:42.660 --> 00:55:48.420
about first fives? What about earlier? What
about preschool? You know, you are starting

00:55:48.420 --> 00:55:53.030
with children who've already had years of
exposure to chicken nuggets shaped like dinosaurs

00:55:53.030 --> 00:55:58.180
and apples that were pre cut in a bag. Why
didn't you start in preschools and get them

00:55:58.180 --> 00:55:59.359
eating healthy there?

00:55:59.359 --> 00:56:03.930
Ann Cooper: We actually, in Berkeley and in
Boulder where preschools are involved with

00:56:03.930 --> 00:56:10.150
the public school system, we do but as an
entry point the public school system is where

00:56:10.150 --> 00:56:15.579
we feed the most kids and because that system
is where we're actually paid, there is money

00:56:15.579 --> 00:56:19.960
available to do that so I'm not at all saying
we shouldn't start with younger kids. It's

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:26.180
just the entry point that I think is one we
can use but most schools are actually starting

00:56:26.180 --> 00:56:31.299
with pre kindergarten and stuff like that
so you do have an option. The thing about

00:56:31.299 --> 00:56:35.849
a lot of the preschools is that they end before
lunch, a lot of preschools are half day so

00:56:35.849 --> 00:56:39.119
we are trying to get into the schools with
breakfast so I absolutely agree. I mean, not

00:56:39.119 --> 00:56:43.130
only you can touch the kids, the more you
can touch the parents. I mean, we go to every

00:56:43.130 --> 00:56:48.329
PTA meeting, these calendars are an unbelievable
marketing tool. I mean the marketing, marketing,

00:56:48.329 --> 00:56:55.809
marketing talking to parents. I mean, it's
hard. I met with a bunch of the leaders of

00:56:55.809 --> 00:57:00.760
the Hispanic community in Boulder a couple
of days ago and getting them to understand

00:57:00.760 --> 00:57:09.569
why it's so important and why we really have
to do this is a process. It takes time and

00:57:09.569 --> 00:57:10.569
it's not easy.

00:57:10.569 --> 00:57:17.550
Olivia Wu: So an interesting point for discussion
later on in a sense. If you want to fight

00:57:17.550 --> 00:57:22.720
the fight, we need to maybe start with the
preschool and consider that this generation

00:57:22.720 --> 00:57:29.980
of high school kids is lost and focus there.
So, thank you for coming and thank you so

00:57:29.980 --> 00:57:36.920
much, Ann, and I know most of us will be continuing
with this discussion for the next two hours.

00:57:36.920 --> 00:57:38.039
Thank you so much.

00:57:38.039 --> 00:57:39.039
Ann Cooper: Thank you.

